The built-in Java Textmate grammar has several highlighting inconsistencies/errors.
atom/language-java (https://github.com/atom/language-java/commit/7a42895fead16e2c39c6667fc9e7ce0f7f922ac4)

- Variables/constants starting with a capital letter are scoped as `storage.type.java`
- Angle brackets are inconsistently scoped, either as
    - keyword.operator.comparison.java
    - keyword.operator.bitwise.java
    - punctuation.bracket.angle.java
- Fields are highlighted incorrectly/differently depending on access modifier
- See images below

![screen shot 2018-02-11 at 11 42 22](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/31404215/36072494-c93b5820-0f20-11e8-85cd-bea9b6615360.png)

## Steps to reproduce:
1. Use built in Monokai color theme (or other colorful theme)
2. Set syntax to "Java"
3. Write _completely normal_ Java code or paste the following example code:
```Java
public class Main {
    // with/without access modifier:
    public
    Set<Map.Entry<K, V>> entrySet0;
    Set<Map.Entry<K, V>> entrySet1;

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Set<Map.Entry<K, V>> entrySet0;
        Node<K, V> m = someNode;
        Node<K, V> first = (Node<K, V>) someValue;
    }

    public static void method() {
        final int MY_CONSTANT = 0;
        int a = MY_CONSTANT + 1;

        int A = 1, B = 2;
        boolean less = A < B;
    }
}
```


![screen shot 2018-02-11 at 11 43 23](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/31404215/36072493-c9205dc2-0f20-11e8-922b-5326720179ee.png)

_Copied from original issue: Microsoft/vscode#43414_

I suggest tokenizing `...` as `punctuation.definition.parameter.vararg`

```java
